{{Infobox coat of arms |name = Coat of arms of the Azores |image = Azr.png |image_width = 200 |armiger = [[Azores|Azores Autonomous Region]] |year_adopted = 10 April 1979 |crest = |torse = |shield = |supporters = |compartment = |motto = |orders = |other_elements = |earlier_versions = |use = }}
The '''coat of arms of the [[Azores]]''' is nine gold stars superimposed on a red bordure, representing the nine islands of the archipelago. The bordure surrounds a silver shield on which a blue eagle is displayed with wings elevated and with red feet, beak, and tongue. The crest is a closed helm in gold lined with red, surmounted by a wreath and mantling of silver and blue, topped by another blue eagle on which are superimposed the same nine gold stars.
The shield is supported by two chained black bulls, above a scroll containing the motto ''Antes morrer livres que em paz sujeitos'' ({{lang-en|Rather die free than in peace be subjugated}}). The supporters each hold a flagpole. Their collars, chains, and hooves are gold, their horns silver. The flags bear Christian symbols. The flag dexter, that is, on the viewer's left, is the red cross of the [[Order of Christ (Portugal)|Portuguese Order of Christ]] on a white field. The flag sinister, that is, on the viewer's right, is a white dove superimposed on gold rays in the shape of a cross - the emblem of the [[Holy Spirit]] - on a red field, both flags bordered in gold.
Early Portuguese visitors mistook the local variety of [[buzzard]], ''[[Common Buzzard|Buteo buteo rothschildi]]'', for [[Northern Goshawk|goshawk]]s (''Accipiter gentilis'') and the [[Portuguese (language)|Portuguese]] word for "goshawk", ''açor'' (pl. ''açores''), is the root of the islands' name.<ref>[http://www.fotw.us/Flags/pt-a.html#flag Azores], September 1999, Flags of the World website. Accessed May 21, 2008.</ref> Goshawks also remain a common motif in Azorean [[heraldry]] and [[vexillology]].
