'''Reflex''' was a 3D building design software application developed in the mid 1980s and - along with its predecessor [[Sonata (building design software)|Sonata]] - is now regarded as a forerunner to today's [[building information modeling|building information modelling]] applications.<ref name=Eastman1>{{cite book|last1=Eastman|first1=Chuck|last2=Tiecholz|first2=Paul|last3=Sacks|first3=Rafael|last4=Liston|first4=Kathleen|title=BIM Handbook: a Guide to Building Information Modeling for owners, managers, designers, engineers, and contractors|date=2008|publisher=John Wiley|location=Hoboken, New Jersey|isbn=9780470185285|edition=1st|pages=xi–xii}}</ref><ref name=Eastman2>{{cite book|last1= Eastman|first1=Chuck|last2=Tiecholz|first2=Paul|last3=Sacks|first3=Rafael|last4=Liston|first4=Kathleen|year = 2011 | title = BIM Handbook: A Guide to Building Information Modeling for Owners, Managers, Designers, Engineers and Contractors | location = Hoboken, New Jersey|publisher=John Wiley|edition=2nd |pages=36–37}}</ref><ref name=Quirk>{{cite web|last1=Quirk|first1=Vanessa|title=A Brief History of BIM|url=http://www.archdaily.com/302490/a-brief-history-of-bim|website=Arch Daily|date=7 December 2012|accessdate=17 October 2015}}</ref><ref name=Andia>{{cite book|last1=Andia|first1=Alfredo|last2=Spiegelhalter|first2=Thomas|title=Post-Parametric Automation in Design and Construction|date=2014|publisher=Artech House|isbn=9781608076949|page=22}}</ref>
==History== The application was developed by two former [[GMW Architects|GMW Computers]] employees who had been involved with Sonata. After Sonata had "disappeared in a mysterious, corporate black hole, somewhere in eastern Canada in 1992,"<ref name=Crotty71>Crotty, p.71</ref> Jonathan Ingram and colleague Gerard Gartside then went on to develop Reflex, bought for $30 million by Parametric Technology Corporation ([[PTC (software company)|PTC]]) in July 1996.<ref name=Crotty71 /><ref>[http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Parametric+Technology+Corporation+acquires+object-oriented+software...-a018490068 Parametric Technology Corporation acquires object-oriented software technology for project modeling and management] PTC news release dated 11 July 1996 (archived at FreeLibrary.com). Retrieved: 17 October 2015.</ref>
PTC had identified the architecture, engineering and construction market as a target for its parametric modelling solutions, and bought Reflex to expand into the sector. However, the fit between Reflex and PTC's existing solutions was poor, and PTC's Pro/Reflex gained little market traction; PTC then sold the product to another US company, [[The Beck Group|Beck Construction]], in 1997,<ref name=Crotty72>Crotty, p.72</ref>{{efn|Some accounts of the date of this transaction vary: Beck Technology, originally an internal group within Beck Construction, says it acquired the intellectual property rights to Reflex from PTC in 2000.<ref>[http://beck-technology.com/about_us.html Beck Technology: About us], Beck Technology. Accessed: 17 October 2015.</ref>}} where it formed the kernel of a parametric estimating package called DESTINI.<ref name=Weisberg /><ref>[http://www.mobilitytechzone.com/news/2006/12/19/2179097.htm BIM software integrates RSMeans for project costing], ''Mobility Techzone'', December 19, 2006. Retrieved: 17 October 2015.</ref>
Around the same time, several people from PTC set up a new company, Charles River Software (renamed [[Autodesk Revit|Revit]] Technology Corporation in 2000, later (2002) bought by [[Autodesk]]).<ref name=Crotty72 /><ref name=Weisberg>Weisberg, David (2008), ''The Engineering Design Revolution: The People, Companies and Computer Systems That Changed Forever the Practice of Engineering''. Chapter 16. Available [http://cadhistory.net/ online]. Retrieved: 17 October 2015</ref> [[Leonid Raiz]] and [[Irwin Jungreis]] obtained from PTC a non-exclusive, source code development license for Reflex as part of their severance package. In the words of Jerry Laiserin: "While Autodesk Revit may not contain genomic snippets of Reflex code, Revit clearly is spiritual heir to a lineage of BIM 'begats' — RUCAPS begat Sonata, Sonata begat Reflex, and Reflex begat Revit."<ref>Laiserin, J. (2003) "[http://laiserin.com/features/issue17/feature02.php LaiserinLetterLetters]" (see Laiserin's comment to letter from John Mullan), ''The Laiserin Letter'', January 06 2003.{{unreliable source?|date=June 2015}}</ref>
In a 2017 letter to ''AEC Magazine,'' Jungreis said: :"After receiving several hours of instruction in the software architecture of Reflex from Reflex developers, we decided not to use it as our starting point because of several important differences at the very foundations of the software. At that point, we put it aside and never looked at it again. ... Revit was not based on Reflex. No code from Reflex was used...."<ref name="AECM-25May2017">{{cite news|title=Celebrating the history of BIM (In response to this article, Dr. Irwin Jungreis, one of the founders of Revit, submitted a letter to AEC Magazine, reproduced in full.)|url=http://aecmag.com/59-features/1352-celebrating-the-history-of-bim|accessdate=21 August 2017|work=AEC Magazine|date=25 May 2017}}</ref>
